GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
S 3
SENATE BILL 416
Judiciary Committee Substitute Adopted 5/6/25
Third Edition Engrossed 5/7/25
Short Title: Personal Privacy Protection Act. (Public)
Sponsors:
Referred to:
March 25, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ENACT THE PERSONAL PRIVACY PROTECTION ACT.
3 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
4 SECTION 1. Chapter 55A of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
5 Article to read:
6 "Article 18.
7 "The Personal Privacy Protection Act.
8 "§ 55A-18-01. Short title.
9 This Article may be cited as The Personal Privacy Protection Act.
10 "§ 55A-18-02. Purpose.
11 This Article prohibits public agencies from collecting, disclosing, or releasing personal
12 information about members, volunteers, and financial and nonfinancial donors to 501(c)
13 nonprofit organizations, except as permitted by State or federal law or regulation. This Article
14 provides penalties for violation of these privacy protections.
15 "§ 55A-18-03. Definitions.
16 In this Article, the following definitions apply:
17 (1) Nonprofit organization. – An entity that (i) is exempt from federal income tax
18 under section 501(c) of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986 or any successor
19 section, (ii) has submitted an application with the Internal Revenue Service
20 for recognition of an exemption under section 501(c) of the Internal Revenue
21 Code of 1986 or any successor section, or (iii) is a not-for-profit business
22 entity recognized under State law.
23 (2) Person. – As defined in G.S. 12-3.
24 (3) Personal information. – Any list, record, register, registry, roll, roster, or other
25 compilation of data of any kind that directly or indirectly identifies a person
26 as a member, supporter, volunteer, or donor of financial or nonfinancial
27 support to any nonprofit organization. For the purposes of this Article, the
28 terms "supporter" and "volunteer" shall not include members of the governing
29 board, officers, directors, or staff of a nonprofit organization.
30 (4) Public agency. – Any State or local governmental unit and its employees,
31 however designated, including, but not limited to, this State; any department,
32 agency, office, commission, board, division, or other entity of this State,
33 including all boards, departments, and divisions; any political subdivision of
34 this State, including, but not limited to, a county, city, local school
35 administrative unit, community college, or any other local governmental unit,
*S416-v-3*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 agency, authority, council, board, or commission; or any State or local court,
2 tribunal, or other judicial or quasi-judicial body.
3 "§ 55A-18-04. Protections afforded.
4 (a) Except as provided in G.S. 55A-18-05 of this Article, a public agency shall not do
5 any of the following:
6 (1) Require any person or nonprofit organization to provide the public agency
7 with personal information or otherwise compel the release of personal
8 information.
9 (2) Release, publicize, or otherwise publicly disclose personal information in
10 possession of the public agency.
11 (3) Request or require a current or prospective contractor or grantee with the
12 public agency to provide a list of nonprofit organizations to which the current
13 or prospective contractor or grantee has provided financial or nonfinancial
14 support.
15 (b) Personal information is not a public record under Chapter 132 of the General Statutes.
16 "§ 55A-18-05. Exemptions.
17 This Article does not preclude any of the following:
18 (1) Reporting or disclosure required by Article 22A of Chapter 163 of the General
19 Statutes.
20 (2) Issuing of a lawful warrant for personal information by a court of competent
21 jurisdiction.
22 (3) Request for discovery of personal information in litigation if both of the
23 following conditions are met:
24 a. The requestor demonstrates a compelling need for the personal
25 information by clear and convincing evidence.
26 b. The requestor obtains a protective order barring disclosure of personal
27 information to any person not named in the litigation.
28 (4) Admission of personal information as relevant evidence before a court of
29 competent jurisdiction. However, no court shall publicly reveal personal
30 information absent a specific finding of good cause.
31 (5) Releasing personal information by a public agency that was voluntarily
32 released to the public by the person or the nonprofit organization to which it
33 relates.
34 (6) Collection of information disclosing the identity of any director, officer,
35 registered agent, or incorporator of a nonprofit organization in any report or
36 disclosure required by statute to be filed with the Secretary of State. This
37 Article does not preclude an audit, examination, review, or investigation
38 pursuant to the authority of the Secretary of State under Chapters 10B, 55A,
39 78A, 78C, 78D, 120C, or 131F of the General Statutes so long as both of the
40 following apply:
41 a. The personal information is only used in connection with the specific
42 audit, examination, review, or investigation to which the request
43 relates and for any related proceedings.
44 b. Any personal information collected otherwise remains subject to
45 G.S. 55A-18-04(a)(2), unless expressly required by law to be publicly
46 disclosed.
47 (7) Disclosure of personal information derived from a donation to a nonprofit
48 organization that is affiliated with a public agency and required by statute, if
49 the person has not previously requested anonymity from the nonprofit
50 organization.
